    <detaileddescription>
<para>&quot;&quot;_hex is a compile-time user-defined literal returning a <computeroutput>std::array&lt;std::byte&gt;</computeroutput>, equivalent to <ref refid="strencodings_8h_1a882aa30dcd768538f02d7e710bf44dc9" kindref="member">ParseHex()</ref>. Variants provided:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>&quot;&quot;_hex_v: Returns <computeroutput>std::vector&lt;std::byte&gt;</computeroutput>, useful for heap allocation or variable-length serialization.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>&quot;&quot;_hex_u8: Returns <computeroutput>std::array&lt;uint8_t&gt;</computeroutput>, for cases where <computeroutput>std::byte</computeroutput> is incompatible.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>&quot;&quot;_hex_v_u8: Returns <computeroutput>std::vector&lt;uint8_t&gt;</computeroutput>, combining heap allocation with <computeroutput>uint8_t</computeroutput>.</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para><simplesect kind="warning"><para>It could be necessary to use vector instead of array variants when serializing, or vice versa, because vectors are assumed to be variable- length and serialized with a size prefix, while arrays are considered fixed length and serialized with no prefix.</para>
</simplesect>
<simplesect kind="warning"><para>It may be preferable to use vector variants to save stack space when declaring local variables if hex strings are large. Alternatively variables could be declared constexpr to avoid using stack space.</para>
</simplesect>
<simplesect kind="warning"><para>Avoid <computeroutput>uint8_t</computeroutput> variants when not necessary, as the codebase migrates to use <computeroutput>std::byte</computeroutput> instead of <computeroutput>unsigned char</computeroutput> and <computeroutput>uint8_t</computeroutput>.</para>
</simplesect>
<simplesect kind="note"><para>One reason &quot;&quot;_hex uses <computeroutput>std::array</computeroutput> instead of <computeroutput>std::vector</computeroutput> like <ref refid="strencodings_8h_1a882aa30dcd768538f02d7e710bf44dc9" kindref="member">ParseHex()</ref> does is because heap-based containers cannot cross the compile- time/runtime barrier. </para>
</simplesect>
</para>
    </detaileddescription>
